6.  The expert’s deliverables are 
(i)  inception, progress, and final reports; 
(ii)  a historical stress scenario database for the CBRC; 
(iii)  technical inputs into the CBRC’s new Guidance on Commercial Banks’ Stress 
Testing;  
(iv)  technical instructions; and 
(v)  technical inputs into the design and implementation of the stress tests, as well as 
the policy brief. 

2.  Senior Stress Test Expert and Deputy Team Leader (national, 9.5 person-
months, intermittent) 

7.  The expert should have 
(i)  a PhD in related areas or a senior professional title; 
(ii)  over 10 years of experience in stress testing for banks in the People's Republic 
of China (PRC) or the banking industry, preferably on bank risk management; 
(iii)  experience in dealing with macroeconomic and financial crises; 
(iv)  knowledge  of  up-to-date  international  techniques  on  stress  testing,  and 
quantitative and modeling techniques; 
(v)  experience in risk management, including credit risk, liquidity risk, and market 
risk; 
(vi)  a good understanding of CBRC supervision policies, including CBRC guidance 
and policies on stress testing, and knowledge of relevant issues in the PRC 
economy and the banking industry; 
(vii)  strong  management  skills  and  experience  in  conducting  training  for  various 
organizations; and 
(viii)  good verbal and written communications, particularly in the English language. 

8.  The expert’s key tasks are to 
(i)  assist the senior stress test expert and team leader in providing guidance and 
supervision to other team members; 
(ii)  conceptualize and design training curricula and materials, and take the lead in 
the conduct of training; 
(iii)  prepare a white paper and the CBRC’s new Guidance on Commercial Banks’ 
Stress Testing; and 
(iv)  design  the  stress  testing  methodology,  modifying  one  adapted  from  the 
Standards  Implementation  Group  of  the  Basel  Committee  on  Banking 
Supervision and tailoring it to the banking conditions in the PRC, and take the 
lead in stress tests. 

9.  The expert’s deliverables are 
(i)  input for inception, progress, and final reports; 
(ii)  recommendations to improve the database; 
(iii)  white  paper  and  the  CBRC’s  new  Guidance  on  Commercial  Banks’  Stress 
Testing;
